[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating build.gradle tests**\n\nI’m considering whether to edit the build.gradle file for rule tests to ensure they only run under the target test source root. It seems likely that using the public API under javaTest might generate the necessary metadata for the coverage report. However, the report indicates that newly covered methods remain uncounted after the JVM passes. This might be due to filtering on direct method handle calls, needing closer observation regarding class initialization and reporting discrepancies.\n\n**Assessing Class.forName behavior**\n\nI’m pondering whether Class.forName might be called from a closure class loaded by the system classloader, but it seems instrumentation may ignore reflective invocations since they're not public API. The coverage report might exclude tests using reflection directly, tracking only dynamically reachable accesses. There seems to be a contradiction where method handles won't show coverage, likely due to how the call stack is classified. I’ll need to investigate the jar file further and explore how Groovy handles static compilation with `$get$$class$`.\n\n**Exploring reflection and coverage**\n\nI’m considering that if the report only expects direct method calls, then that might be the only way to address the issue. However, if direct invocation shows no coverage, maybe I should invoke it using Java reflection instead of method handles. My first attempt with Groovy's `metaClass.invokeStaticMethod` may not have worked due to how Groovy handles method resolution. It’s possible that the agent only instruments reflection calls at the bytecode level, which might prevent coverage for package-private method invocations. I need to dig deeper into this.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0d7bbb64cda8a81b016a27b62e5cb48195bab5ce5700b9543d\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJ7